    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3514420311" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3514420311" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78330000-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1622677847p2/78330000.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3514420311?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/78330000-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141985138" href="/book/show/41728446-how-to-change-your-mind">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/78330000-sarah?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3514420311" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6100640867443557722"><b>WOW!</b> Sometimes you read something that is so eye opening and this is most certainly one of those books for me. Having always been intrigued by psychedelics and their effects on brain chemistry in particular - this was an unbelievably interesting, informative study. Especially from a philosophical and psychological viewpoint. It is easy to be fearful of these types of drugs and the effects they can have on people - nobody wants to experience a bad trip. <br/>Also, this opens up a great discussion abou</span>
  <span id="freeText6100640867443557722" style="display:none"><b>WOW!</b> Sometimes you read something that is so eye opening and this is most certainly one of those books for me. Having always been intrigued by psychedelics and their effects on brain chemistry in particular - this was an unbelievably interesting, informative study. Especially from a philosophical and psychological viewpoint. It is easy to be fearful of these types of drugs and the effects they can have on people - nobody wants to experience a bad trip. <br />Also, this opens up a great discussion about how science and spiritualism can go hand in hand and balance each other out to gain a greater understanding of the human psyche. <br /><br />The first chapter discusses the birth of Lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD) by Albert Hoffmann. It is then discussed how the drug was used in the 1950s by the CIA for the infamous <i>”MK-Ultra”</i> “mind control” experiments. Then the huge boom of LSD use in the 1960s, particularly the 1967 <i>Summer Of Love</i>, yet it had already been made illegal by 1966 (made a federal crime for possession by 1968). <br />This was assisted by Timothy Leary, a Harvard Professor, whose own experiments had little scientific merit.<br /><br />Michael Pollen is a novice to the world of psychedelics - having taken mushrooms in his youth and being yet to try LSD. Before trying them for this very book, he trips on frog venom and believes that he has given birth to himself. <br /><br /><i>How To Change Your Mind</i> asks the question if psychedelics could (in measured doses) help to improve certain mental illnesses, such as decreasing anxiety, and improve quality of life?<br />It makes one wonder how many more advancements would have been made if psychedelic drugs hadn’t been made illegal. Especially considering the success rates of some of the experiments recorded. This is a debate worth having. <br />There is evidence that psilocybin can alter a person’s perception and outlook on life as a whole from the experiences they have whilst taking it. Also it has been used experimentally to treat addictions to alcohol and smoking. <br />People who volunteered to take psilocybin were told they may experience the <i>”death/transcendence of your ego or everyday self”</i> but this is <i>”always followed by Rebirth/Return to the normative world of space &amp; time. Safest way to return to normal is to entrust self unconditionally to the emerging experience.”</i><br /><br />A particularly interesting paragraph highlights how, at UCLA, microdoses of MDMA have been used to treat patients with PTSD and also social anxiety in autistic adults. <br /><br />Aldous Huxley’s <i>The Doors Of Perception</i> is referenced throughout. I have been meaning to check this title out for many years, and shall be doing so soon. <br /><br /><i>”Mysticism is the antidote to fundamentalism.”</i> 🍄✨🖤</span>
  <a data-text-id="6100640867443557722" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


